    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nHi there!\n\nHistorically I had an issue that nvim doesn't restore cursor shape to the original state when it exits.\nSo, even if I had l-shape blinking cursor in terminal emulator, nvim leaves \"static block\" after exit.\n\nSo, I have added this to my config long time ago as a workaround:\n```lua\nvim.api.nvim_create_autocmd(\"VimLeave\", {pattern = \"*\", callback = function()\n  vim.o.guicursor = \"a:ver1-Cursor/lCursor-blinkon1\"\nend})\n```\n\nSo, it worked for years, until some recent time (I actually didn't catch the exact moment)\n\nNow `nvim` with that hack and different `TERM`'s in different tested terminals it doesn't work \"as expected\", but in different ways...\n\n\n# In `Konsole`:\nWith `TERM=konsole-256color` (and other konsole-related ones) nvim restores \"blinking\", but not the shape.\n\nInteresting thing, that with `TERM=xterm-256color` (and siblings) or `TERM=tmux-256color` (and siblings) it do restore the shape, but not blinking 😀 \n\nN.B.: here, and in two next terminals (not `tmux`) too, I just used `tmux-*` TERM for testing purposes, `tmux` itself was not used in the experiment.\n\n# In `xterm`:\nWith both it's default `TERM=xterm` and with `TERM=xterm-256color`, and even with `TERM=tmux-256color` cursor always anywas become a static block.\n\n# In `vte`:\nBy default it uses `TERM=xterm-256color` and `nvim` restores nothing on exit with that (cursor become static block)\nAfter setting `TERM=vte-256color`, `nvim` restores blinking on exit, but cursor become block anyway.\nWith `TERM=tmux-256color` it is also become a static block.\n\n# in, well, `tmux` 😀  (running in `Konsole`):\nwith `TERM=tmux-256color`, `nvim` restores l-shape on exit, but not blinking.\nSame with `TERM=xterm-256color`.\n(!!!!!) But with `TERM=konsole-256color`, `nvim` do restore all as expected (both l-shape and blinking).\n\n\n# `tmux` in `vte`:\nRestores nothing with `TERM=tmux-256color`.\nRestores blinking (but not shape) with `TERM=vte-256color`\n(!!!!!) But with `TERM=konsole-256color`, `nvim` do restore all as expected (both l-shape and blinking).\n\n# `tmux` in `xterm`:\nRestores nothing with `TERM=tmux-256color` or `TERM=xterm-256color`.\n(lol) Restores blinking (but not shape) with `TERM=vte-256color` 😀 \n(!!!!!) But with `TERM=konsole-256color`, `nvim` do restore all as expected (both l-shape and blinking).\n\n------\n\nSo, it seems, there was something broken (again) in terminal detection code in nvim.\nUnfortunatelly, this time I have not enough spare time to make a PR, so can somebody fix it (again), please?\n\n\n\n------\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n```\nnvim --clean 1\n:lua vim.api.nvim_create_autocmd(\"VimLeave\", {pattern = \"*\", callback = function() vim.o.guicursor = \"a:ver1-Cursor/lCursor-blinkon1\" end})\n:q\n```\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nCursor restores at least as set in autocommand (while ideally `nvim` would do that itself, without even autocommand)\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\n0.2.12 | nightly\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nnot applicable (hack relies on nvim api)\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nGentoo\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nKonsole/Yakuake 26.04.1 || xterm-406 || vte-0.80.4 (2.91 api version)\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\n(many different, see in description above)\n\n### Installation\n\nsystem package manager (0.2.12) | nightly appimage",
